rmk:
Recorded:

  • contact-alarm call, tyew-tyew, e.g. at 0:00.2, 0:03.2 and 0:13.6
  • chip call, tyip-tyip-tyip... or chip-chip-chip..., at e.g. 0:04.2, then from 0:15.6 and onwards

General observations: Small lake, close to the mountain tree-line. Mainly spruce trees and mountain birches. Greenshank flies in a 100 metres wide circle calling and then flies away out of reach of the recording equipment. Temperature: 17°C/62.6 °F. Southerly wind, light breeze.

Recording remarks: The tyew and tyip notes are mixed in the beginning of the recording, where tyew being slightly longer and with less steep slope in pitch. Some notes are of an intermediate form between the two types of calls. From 0:15.6 the tyip call is dominating and the notes are repeated more rapidly, according to the same structure as e.g. XC663698

Classification and rendering: NatureGuides, 2020, Birds of Western Palearctic, AppStore.

Recording equipment: Dodotronic Hi-sound Stereo AOL Parabolic Microphone, Sony PCM-A10 Recorder.
